# Release Operations Rules

> **Activation guard**: Apply this rule when working on release operations (skills under `.cursor/skills/release/`, commands starting with `release-*` or `hotfix-*`, or any task referencing the weekly release cycle). Do NOT apply for unrelated tasks.

## Release Model: Image Tagging

This team has **no staging environment**. Image builds happen **after** PR merge to `dev`. QA is performed on the `dev` environment using a frozen RC image. The release flow uses an **opt-in label policy** combined with **immutable image promotion** to prevent unverified changes from reaching production.

### Fundamental Principle: Freeze the Artifact, Not the Branch

Every PR merged to `dev` triggers a CI build that produces a `dev-{TIMESTAMP}` container image pushed to `ghcr.io`. On release collection day, the Release Owner selects the `dev` HEAD image and re-tags it as `rc-{TIMESTAMP}`. QA verifies this exact image. On deployment day, the verified RC image is promoted to a production tag `vYYYY.MM.DD`. No branch cuts, no reverts, no merge conflicts.

### Opt-In, Not Opt-Out

Every PR merged to `dev` is **excluded by default** from the weekly release. App owners must explicitly approve their PR for inclusion by adding the `release:approved` label after verifying the change works in the `dev` environment.

## 7 Core Rules

1. **No `release:approved` label → Excluded from release**
   A merged PR is included in the RC ONLY if the app owner has added `release:approved` after verifying the change in dev. Unlabeled PRs are auto-held at Tuesday cutoff.

2. **No QA result by Wednesday EOD → No Thursday deployment**
   Every item in the RC must have a recorded QA result (Pass, Fail, or Conditional Pass) by end of Wednesday. Items without QA results are excluded and the RC image may be rebuilt.

3. **Hotfixes require impact statement and notification status**
   Every hotfix MUST include: customer/business impact description, business team notification status, and QA completion status. Hotfixes missing any of these are blocked.

4. **Every item needs an accountable app owner**
   Each release item MUST have an assigned app owner who can explain the change, its impact, and the rollback plan. Orphaned items (no assignee) are excluded.

5. **No new items on deployment day**
   Thursday's release list is locked. New items CANNOT be added on deployment day. The only exception is approved hotfixes through the `#hotfix-alert` channel.

6. **PR description must have the 5 required sections**
   Every PR labeled `release:approved` or `hotfix` MUST have all 5 sections filled: Changes, User Impact, QA Method, Rollback Method, Related Issue/Ticket.

7. **`release:approved` and `hotfix` are mutually exclusive**
   A single PR CANNOT carry both. Regular releases follow the weekly cycle; hotfixes follow the emergency path.

## GitHub Label Taxonomy

### Release Inclusion Labels (3-Label Gate System)

| Label | Meaning | Default State | Who Applies | When |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `release:approved` | Verified in dev, include in this week's release | — | App owner | After testing in dev, before Monday EOD |
| `release:hold` | Intentionally deferred to next cycle | — | App owner | Anytime — WIP, dependency, timing reasons |
| `release:blocked` | Issues found in dev, must NOT ship | — | App owner or QA | When bugs discovered in dev |
| *(no release label)* | Treated as `release:hold` at Tuesday cutoff | This is the default | — | Auto-applied Tuesday 10:00 AM |

**Key constraint**: Only `release:approved` PRs are included. Everything else is excluded.

### PR Lifecycle After Merge

```
PR merged to dev
  → CI builds dev-{TIMESTAMP} image → pushes to ghcr.io
  → Image deployed to dev environment
  → App owner tests in dev
    ├─ Works correctly    → add `release:approved` + `risk:*`
    ├─ Not ready/WIP      → add `release:hold` (or leave unlabeled)
    └─ Bug found          → add `release:blocked`
```

### Existing Labels (already on the repo)

| Category | Labels | Usage in Release Ops |
|---|---|---|
| Change type | `bug`, `enhancement`, `feature`, `refactoring`, `performance`, `chore`, `security` | Classify what kind of change the PR is. |
| Area | `backend`, `pods-service`, `workloads-eda` | Identify which service/area is affected. |
| Severity | `severity:critical` | Marks critical issues; maps to `risk:high`. |
| Process | `deployment`, `testing` | Infra/deploy changes or test-only PRs. |
| Automation | `automated`, `dependencies`, `github_actions` | Auto-generated PRs. Usually low risk. |

### New Labels (created for release ops)

```bash
# Release inclusion gate (3-label system)
gh label create "release:approved" --color "0E8A16" --description "PR approved for weekly release"
gh label create "release:hold" --color "FBCA04" --description "PR held from release (needs review)"
gh label create "release:blocked" --color "B60205" --description "PR blocked from release"

# Hotfix
gh label create "hotfix" --color "D93F0B" --description "Urgent fix outside regular cycle"

# QA status
gh label create "qa:needed" --color "1D76DB" --description "QA verification required"
gh label create "qa:done" --color "0E8A16" --description "QA verification completed"

# Risk classification
gh label create "risk:low" --color "C2E0C6" --description "Low deployment risk"
gh label create "risk:medium" --color "FBCA04" --description "Medium deployment risk"
gh label create "risk:high" --color "B60205" --description "High deployment risk"
```

### Validation

A merged PR is considered **release-ready** when it has:
1. `release:approved` label (mandatory — opt-in gate)
2. Exactly one `risk:*` label (`risk:low`, `risk:medium`, `risk:high`)
3. At least one area/type label from existing labels
4. PR description with all 5 required sections filled
5. An assignee (app owner)

### Risk Mapping from Existing Labels

| Existing label pattern | Default risk | Rationale |
|---|---|---|
| `dependencies` or `automated` | `risk:low` | Auto-generated, scoped changes |
| `refactoring` or `chore` or `testing` | `risk:low` | No user-facing behavior change |
| `bug` or `performance` | `risk:medium` | Behavior change, but targeted fix |
| `security` or `severity:critical` | `risk:high` | Broad impact, requires careful rollback |
| `deployment` or `feature` or `enhancement` | `risk:medium` | New functionality or infra — assess per case |

## Image Tagging Model (No Staging)

### Image Tag Scheme

| Tag Pattern | Purpose | Lifecycle |
|---|---|---|
| `dev-{TIMESTAMP}` | Built from every `dev` merge | Ephemeral; overwritten by next merge |
| `rc-{TIMESTAMP}` | Release Candidate — frozen artifact for QA | Created at Tuesday collection; immutable |
| `vYYYY.MM.DD` | Production release tag | Created at Thursday deploy; permanent |

### Weekly Flow

```
After merge    │ CI builds dev-{TIMESTAMP} image → ghcr.io
After merge    │ App owner tests in dev, applies release:approved
Mon 18:00      │ Bot sends reminder for unlabeled merged PRs
Tue 10:00      │ CUTOFF: unlabeled PRs → auto release:hold
Tue 10:00      │ Release Owner collects release:approved PRs
Tue 10:30      │ CI re-tags dev HEAD image as rc-{TIMESTAMP}
Tue 11:00      │ RC image deployed to dev env for QA
Tue PM         │ Notify QA team: RC image ready on dev
Wed all-day    │ QA on dev environment (running RC image)
Wed EOD        │ QA gate: pass/fail for each item
Thu AM         │ Promote RC image → tag as vYYYY.MM.DD
Thu AM         │ Deploy vYYYY.MM.DD to production via ArgoCD
Thu PM         │ Restore dev env to latest dev HEAD image
```

### RC Image Creation Process

```bash
# 1. Identify the last release tag
LAST_RELEASE=$(git tag --list 'v20*' --sort=-creatordate | head -1)

# 2. List merged PRs since last release
gh pr list --state merged --base dev \
  --search "merged:>=$(git log -1 --format=%ci $LAST_RELEASE | cut -d' ' -f1)" \
  --json number,title,mergeCommit,labels,assignees

# 3. Classify PRs
#   approved_prs: has release:approved label → included in RC
#   excluded_prs: has release:hold, release:blocked, or NO release label → excluded

# 4. Verify dev HEAD contains all approved PRs
#   If any release:blocked or late-breaking issue requires exclusion:
#     → Option A: choose an earlier dev SHA that excludes the problematic PR
#     → Option B: revert the problematic PR from dev, rebuild dev image, use new HEAD

# 5. Tag the chosen dev image as RC
#   source_tag = dev-{TIMESTAMP} (the current dev HEAD image)
#   rc_tag = rc-$(date +%Y%m%d%H%M%S)
#   Use CI workflow: gh workflow run release-webui.yaml -f image_tag=$rc_tag

# 6. Deploy RC image to dev environment for QA
#   ArgoCD redeploys dev with the RC image tag
```

### Handling Exclusions

When an approved PR must be removed from the RC after collection:

1. **Best case**: The problematic PR was merged recently and dev HEAD without it still contains all other approved PRs. Select an earlier dev image (`dev-{earlier_TIMESTAMP}`) and re-tag as RC.
2. **Revert case**: If the problematic PR is interleaved with other approved changes, revert it from `dev`, wait for CI to rebuild `dev-{new_TIMESTAMP}`, then re-tag as RC.
3. **RC is always a single immutable image** — there is no partial revert on a branch.

### Post-Deploy

After Thursday production deployment:
1. Restore dev environment to latest `dev` HEAD image
2. Tag the RC image as `vYYYY.MM.DD` (permanent production tag)
3. PRs with `release:hold` remain on `dev` for next cycle evaluation
4. PRs with `release:blocked` need fixes before reconsideration

## Weekly Timeline Constraints

| Day | Time | Action | Actor |
|---|---|---|---|
| After merge | Anytime | Test in dev, apply release label | App owner |
| Monday | 18:00 KST | Reminder for unlabeled merged PRs | Bot (GitHub Action) |
| Tuesday | 10:00 KST | Auto-hold unlabeled PRs; collect approved PRs | Bot + Release Owner |
| Tuesday | 10:30 KST | Re-tag dev HEAD image as rc-{TIMESTAMP} | CI/CD |
| Tuesday | 11:00 KST | RC image deployed to dev for QA | CI/CD |
| Wednesday | All day | QA on dev (RC image) | QA team |
| Wednesday | EOD | QA results due | QA team |
| Thursday | AM | Promote RC → vYYYY.MM.DD; deploy to production | Release Owner |
| Thursday | PM | Restore dev to latest HEAD image | Release Owner |

